I visited Centralia for the first and only time this past October. This documentary was supposedly filmed over the course of four years in the mid-2000s, and the amount of identifiable structure this town has lost since then is baffling. I'd believe there used to be hundreds of buildings in this ghost town if it still looked the way it did in 2007. But there's nothing left. There are roads and sidewalks covered with trees. There was a hollowed fire…

It's amazing how perfectly McCarthy's novel falls into Coen canon. This is an absurdly faithful adaptation, yet so much of the themes, the dialogue, the dialect and the archetype and genre deconstructions feel hard-written into an original script. It's bleakness transcends to a technical level as it famously shirks its score over silent stares and pounding gunshots. It's a "cold sweat" suspense flick, the greatest answer to the neo-western, and it has all the elements of an enduring classic, literarily and cinematically.
